      "targetText": "a apăra"
    }
  ],
  "examples": [
    {
      "sourceText": "I attack the opponent.",
      "targetText": "Eu atac adversarul."
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "Are you attacking him?",
      "targetText": "Îl ataci?"
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "The enemy attacks.",
      "targetText": "Dușmanul atacă."
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "We attack first.",
      "targetText": "Noi atacăm mai întâi."
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "Are you attacking the castle?",
      "targetText": "Atacați castelul?"
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "They attack the area.",
      "targetText": "Ei atacă zona."
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "I attacked the plan.",
      "targetText": "Am atacat planul."
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "He attacked whenever he could.",
      "targetText": "El ataca ori de câte ori avea ocazia."
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "I will attack at this point.",
      "targetText": "Voi ataca acest punct."
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "I would attack if I had the chance.",
      "targetText": "Aș ataca dacă aș avea ocazia."
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "Attack!",
      "targetText": "Atacă!"
    }
  ],
  "learningTips": [
    {
      "lang": "en",
      "text": "Remember 'attack' sounds like 'a tack'—imagine tacking down your opponent to win the fight."
    },
    {
      "lang": "en",
      "text": "The Romanian 'a ataca' sounds like 'attack a'—think of it as 'to attack' in Romanian, making it easy to recall."
    },
    {
      "lang": "en",
      "text": "Both 'attack' and 'a ataca' start with 'at-', linking them in your mind as words for aggressive action."
    },
    {
      "lang": "en",
      "text": "Picture a sports match where you 'attack' the goal—this helps connect the English and Romanian verbs."
    }
  ],
